A table of contents (TOC) in LaTeX can be generated automatically using the `\tableofcontents` command. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is placed before the sections of the document. When you compile the document, LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents that lists the sections and their corresponding page numbers.

Here's a breakdown of the commands used:

* `\documentclass{article}`: This specifies the document class, which determines the overall layout and formatting of the document.
* `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`: These commands mark the beginning and end of the document.
* `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents.
* `\section{...}`: These commands define the sections of the document. The text within the curly braces is the title of the section.

To customize the appearance of the table of contents, you can use various options and packages. For example, you can change the font size, spacing, and formatting using commands like `\renewcommand{\contentsname}{Table of Contents}` or `\setlength{\tocdepth}{2}`.

Here's an example of how you can customize the table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\renewcommand{\contentsname}{Table of Contents}
\setlength{\tocdepth}{2}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is the first subsection.

\section{Methods}
This is the methods section.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is the second subsection.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\renewcommand{\contentsname}{Table of Contents}` command changes the title of the table of contents to "Table of Contents", and the `\setlength{\tocdepth}{2}` command sets the depth of the table of contents to 2, which means that only sections and subsections will be included.

